ess Transit|Nottingham Express Tram]] system serves three stops on the western edge of West Bridgford.}} || 45,509<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35000901|title=West Bridgford Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || N/A ||\n|-\n| [[Swadlincote]] || 45,000<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35001337|title=Swadlincote Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1947<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020 |page=387 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> ||A reopening of the line between {{rws|Burton on Trent}} and {{rws|Leicester}} would see a station at {{rws|Gresley}}, south of the town.<ref name=\"RM\"/>\n|-\n| [[Kingswood, South Gloucestershire|Kingswood]] || 40,734 || N/A ||\n|-\n| [[Skelmersdale]] || 34,455<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35001425|title=Skelmersdale Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1963<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Skelmersdale Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/s/skelmersdale/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||Skelmersdale was designated as a '[[New towns in the United Kingdom|new town]]' in 1961, with a focus on people owning cars. However, a proposal is being considered by the [[Lancashire County Council]] and is going through a [[Network Rail#The GRIP process|GRIP 3]] process.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Pickering |first1=Graeme |title=Rail Reopening Schemes |magazine=The Railway Magazine |date=April 2020 |volume=166 |issue=1,429 |page=41 |publisher=Mortons Media |location=Horncastle |issn=0033-8923}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Canvey Island|Canvey]] || 38,170<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E34004293|title=Canvey Island Built-up area|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || N/A ||\n|-\n| [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]] || 37,339<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E34002074|title=Blyth (Northumberland) Built-up area|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1964<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations:Blyth Station (2nd) |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/blyth_second/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || A [[Blyth and Tyne Railway#2019-present: Revised plans and the Northumberland Line project|proposal]] to reopen the freight-only [[Blyth and Tyne Railway]] to passengers has been mooted by SENRUG (South East Northumberland Rail User Group) and [[Northumberland County Council]]. If the line does reopen, a station would be built at {{rws|Newsham}} (south west of Blyth) as the former Blyth Branch is not part of the reopening plans.<ref name=\"TRM\">{{cite magazine|last=Pickering |first=Graeme |title=New targets for Northumberland |magazine=Rail Magazine |date=6 November 2019 |issue=891 |page=46 |publisher=Bauer Media |location=Peterborough |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dunstable]] || 36,253<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E04011941|title=Dunstable Parish|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1965<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Dunstable Town Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/d/dunstable_town/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Coalville]] || 34,575<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35000934|title=Coalville Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1964<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020 |page=123 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> || Proposed for reopening on the line between {{rws|Burton on Trent}} and {{rws|Leicester}}.<ref name=\"RM\">{{cite magazine |last1=Pickering |first1=Graeme |title=Rail Reopening Schemes |magazine=The Railway Magazine |date=April 2020 |volume=166 |issue=1,429 |page=39 |publisher=Mortons Media |location=Horncastle |issn=0033-8923}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] || 33,130<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E04008187|title=Abingdon Parish|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1963<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Abingdon Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/a/abingdon/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Wisbech]] || 31,573<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35000453|title=Wisbech Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1968<ref name=\"QUICK\">{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020 |page=433 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> ||A 2009 report stated that it was feasible to reopen the [[Bramley Line]] to {{rws|March}} railway station for \u00a312&nbsp;million, as the line was extant but unused. Since then, little had been done and the cost had risen to an estimated \u00a370&nbsp;million by 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Johnston|first=Howard|title=Regional News (Anglia) |magazine=Rail Magazine |date=28 August 2019 |issue=886 |page=11 |publisher=Bauer Media |location=Peterborough |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Rushden]] || 29,501<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35000811|title=Rushden Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1969<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Rushden Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/r/rushden/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||Proposals have been put forward for [[Rushden Parkway railway station]] on the [[Midland Main Line]], to the west of the town.\n|-\n| [[Willenhall]] || 28,480<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E05001319|title=Willenhall North Ward (as of 2011)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E05001320|title=Willenhall South Ward (as of 2011)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1965<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020 |page=429 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> || The railway station at [[Willenhall Bilston Street railway station|Willenhall]] has been proposed for reopening by 2040. It is on a freight/diversionary line between {{rws|Wolverhampton}} and {{rws|Walsall}}/{{rws|Tame Bridge}} railway stations.<ref name=\"RAIL\">{{cite magazine|last=Stephen|first=Paul|title=Mayor's \u00a315bn plan for West Midlands rail |magazine=Rail Magazine |date=12 February 2020 |issue=898 |page=11 |publisher=Bauer Media |location=Peterborough |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ashington]] || 27,670<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E34001445|title=Ashington (Northumberland) Built-up area|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1964<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations:Ashington Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/a/ashington/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || A [[Blyth and Tyne Railway#2019-present: Revised plans and the Northumberland Line project|proposal]] to reopen the freight-only [[Blyth and Tyne Railway]] to passengers has been mooted by SENRUG (South East Northumberland Rail User Group) and [[Northumberland County Council]].<ref name=\"TRM\"/>\n|-\n| [[Witney]] || 27,522<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E04008335|title=Witney Parish|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1962<ref name=\"QUICK\"/> ||\n|-\n| [[Haverhill, Suffolk|Haverhill]] || 27,041<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E34000327|title=Haverhill Built-up area|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1967<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Haverhill Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/h/haverhill/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Aldridge]] || 26,988<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E05001301|title=Aldridge Central and South Ward (as of 2011)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E05001302|title=Aldridge North and Walsall Wood Ward (as of 2011)|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>  || 1965<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Sutton Park Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/a/aldridge/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||The railway station at {{rws|Aldridge}} has been proposed for reopening by 2040. It is on a freight/diversionary line between {{rws|Walsall}} and {{rws|Water Orton}} railway stations.<ref name=\"RAIL\"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Padgett |first1=David |last2=Szwenk |first2=John |editor1-last=Bridge |editor1-first=Mike |title=Railway track diagrams. book 4, Midlands & North West |date=2013 |publisher=Trackmaps |location=Bradford on Avon |isbn=978-0-9549866-7-4 |edition=3|at=18}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ferndown]] || 26,559<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35001246|title=Ferndown Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || N/A ||\n|-\n| [[Woodley, Berkshire|Woodley]] || 25,932<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E04001243|title=Woodley Parish|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>  || N/A ||\n|-\n|}\n\nSmaller towns that are not served by railway stations include [[Kingswinford]] in the West Midlands (pop. 25,191), [[Daventry]] in Northamptonshire (pop. 25,026), [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]] in Somerset (pop. 23,699), [[Clevedon]] in Somerset (pop. 21,282), [[Spennymoor]] in County Durham (pop. 19,816), [[Cirencester]] in Gloucestershire (pop. 19,076), [[Guisborough]] in North Yorkshire (pop. 17,777), [[Bideford]] in Devon (pop. 17,107) and [[Oswestry]] in Shropshire (pop. 17,105). {{As of|2020|}}, there are plans afoot to reopen the railway stations at [[Portishead railway station|Portishead]] and [[Oswestry railway station|Oswestry]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Largest towns in England without a railway station}}\n